Exercise 1

Consider the dataset aus_airpassengers, the total number of passengers (in millions) from Australian air carriers for the period 1970-2011.

aus_airpassengers %>% autoplot(Passengers)

  1. Check that applying 2-nd order differences results in a stationary time series. That is:
  • Take first-order differences of Passengers and call the result diff
  • Take subsequent first-order differences of diff to obtain the second order differences and call it diff2
aus_airpassengers <-
  aus_airpassengers %>% 
    mutate(
            diff = difference(Passengers, 1),
            diff2 = difference(diff, 1)
          )

# aus_airpassengers %>% autoplot(diff)
# aus_airpassengers %>% autoplot(diff2)

aus_airpassengers %>%
  features(diff2, unitroot_kpss)
# A tibble: 1 Ã 2
  kpss_stat kpss_pvalue
      <dbl>       <dbl>
1    0.0361         0.1
  1. The second order differences are a stationary process and, as such, an ARMA(p,q) model is sensible for this time series.

2.1 Plot the ACF and PACF of the second order differences (use gg_tsdisplay):

aus_airpassengers %>% gg_tsdisplay(diff2, plot_type="partial")
Warning: Removed 2 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).
Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

2.2 Propose and fit one or more sensible for diff2 models based on the graphs above. Also fit an automatically fitted model using ARIMA(diff2) with no further arguments.

# acf seems to clearly cut-off

# It is unclear from the graph whether pacf tails-off or cuts-off. We therefore
# propose two models:

# Model 1: assume ACF cuts-off and PACF tails-off. This is an MA(1)

# Model 2: assume PACF cuts-off. ACF does not tail off, but we will fit
# an AR(4) matching the cut-off on the pacf.

fit <-
  aus_airpassengers %>% 
    model(
          MA1 = ARIMA(diff2 ~ pdq(0, 0, 1)),
          AR4 = ARIMA(diff2 ~ pdq(4, 0, 0)),
          auto = ARIMA(diff2)
        )

fit %>% glance()

# the auto model is an MA1 model

The distribution looks fairly normal on its central part, deviating at the tails
There seems to be a degree of skewness but mean and median are very close.
Due to the criticality of this assumption in ARIMA.
# Shapiro test and Kolmogorov test
residuals %>% pull(.innov) %>% shapiro.test()

    Shapiro-Wilk normality test

data:  .
W = 0.83823, p-value = 1.849e-05
residuals %>% pull(.innov) %>% ks.test("pnorm")

    Exact one-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test

data:  .
D = 0.15561, p-value = 0.2034
alternative hypothesis: two-sided
Shapiro test identifies data as not normal.
Kolmogorov test identifies data as normal.

In this situation and given the good match of normality to the central region
and the closeness of mean and median we are going to consider the normality
assumption is sufficiently held.

Exercise 2

Consider the United States GDP series (from global_economy)

us_economy <- global_economy %>% filter(Code == "USA")
us_economy %>% autoplot(GDP)

The data has a non-linear trend. We can either perform multiple order differences to remove the non-linear trend or linearize it prior to differencing. Here we are going to opt for this second option.

  1. Perform a box-cox transformation to the data and plot the result
lambda <- us_economy %>%
  features(GDP, features = guerrero) %>%
  pull(lambda_guerrero)
lambda
[1] 0.2819443
us_economy %>%
  autoplot(box_cox(GDP, lambda))

  1. Check that applying first order differences to the box-cox transformed data results in a stationary time series.
us_economy <-
  us_economy %>%
    mutate(
       bc_diff = difference(box_cox(GDP, lambda), 1)
          )

us_economy %>%
  features(bc_diff, unitroot_kpss)
# A tibble: 1 Ã 3
  Country       kpss_stat kpss_pvalue
  <fct>             <dbl>       <dbl>
1 United States     0.208         0.1
  1. Model the resulting stationary time series using ARMA. Plot the ACF and PACF to pick up sensible values for p and q. Also fit an auto-ARIMA model using ARIMA(box_cox(GDP, lambda)) with no further arguments.
us_economy %>% gg_tsdisplay(bc_diff, plot_type="partial")
Warning: Removed 1 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).
Warning: Removed 1 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

# Both ACF and PACF seems to cut-off.

# ACF suggest MA1
# PACF suggest AR1

fit <-
  us_economy %>% 
    model(
        AR1 = ARIMA(box_cox(GDP, lambda) ~ pdq(1, 0, 0)),
        MA1 = ARIMA(box_cox(GDP, lambda) ~ pdq(0, 0, 1)),
        auto = ARIMA(box_cox(GDP, lambda))
      )

Note that only one of the three models has been fit! The AR1 and MA1 models 
lead to models that had coefficients that did not fulfil the root conditions
(complex roots outside the unit circle) and therefore were not fitted.

Only the automatically found model has been fit.
